      "content": "# one operation per user intent keeps concerns separated\n\nEach operation should correspond to a single user action. This keeps operations atomic, testable, and replayable:\n\n```\n✅ ADD_LINE_ITEM — adds one line item\n✅ UPDATE_RECIPIENT — changes the recipient\n✅ SET_DUE_DATE — sets the due date\n\n❌ UPDATE_INVOICE — changes recipient, adds items, and sets date in one operation\n```\n\nDescriptive operation names (e.g., `ADD_LINE_ITEM`, `UPDATE_RECIPIENT`) communicate intent better than generic names (e.g., `UPDATE_DATA`).\n\nSince [[operation design uses descriptive names and includes examples and errors]], each operation should also define error types and include examples in the document model.\n\n---\n\nTopics:\n- [[reducer patterns]]\n- [[schema design]]",
